In January 1938, Milt Gabler started recording for his new label, Commodore Records, and to allow for longer continuous performances, he recorded some of the first jazz albums on this new label. The first album was recorded at the Philharmonic Hall at the Ritz Hotel on July 20. He was at the hotel conducting the Philharmonic Orchestra that he led. During the recording of the album, he appeared to the side of the piano bench and was introduced to an enthusiastic audience while he played, with many people recording the performance (some of these recordings exist in the US as well). Many of the recordings are the original albums (which no longer exist in the US).

